  ],
  "campus": "Atlanta",
  "campus_description": "ATL@ATLANTA",
  "course_description": "Credit variable. Psychology majors only, registration by permission of faculty supervisor.",
  "course_notes": "Experience in programming (Unity, C++, C#, Python), designing and building user-interfaces and user-interaction experiences, whether software, AR/VR/MR/XR, AI, physical interfaces, and electronics will be very helpful as you will be building systems. Highly recommended (but not required) prerequisite courses: CS 334/534: Machine Learning CS 512: Ethics in Computing and AI The field of extended reality for learning broadly examines how immersive technologies such as virtual, augmented, and mixed reality can be designed, studied, and evaluated to support human learning. This is not a programming focused course. Rather, the purpose of this seminar is to investigate the learning, cognitive, and experiential dimensions of XR technologies through the lenses of learning sciences, human computer interaction, and design research. The course emphasizes how XR systems shape perception, embodiment, spatial reasoning, skill acquisition, and knowledge construction. Students will engage with foundational theories of learning and cognition, as well as contemporary research on immersive interaction, feedback design, multimodal sensing, and adaptive instruction. Because XR for learning draws from multiple disciplines, the seminar will expose students to research spanning HCI, cognitive science, education, psychology, artificial intelligence, robotics, manufacturing training, medicine, architecture, and STEM education.",
  "requisites": null,
